message: "If you use this material, please cite it as below."
title: "Executing Author JavaScript in Educational Resources: A Security Evaluation of Isolation in Moodle, WordPress, Omeka S, SCORM, H5P, and eXeLearning"
type: dataset
authors:
  - family-names: Serrano
    given-names: Ernesto
    orcid: "https://orcid.org/0009-0006-3817-1317"
    affiliation: "Independent Researcher, Spain"
    email: info@ernesto.es
repository-code: "https://github.com/erseco/lms-untrusted-content-security-paper"
url: "https://github.com/erseco/lms-untrusted-content-security-paper"
abstract: >-
  An empirical security evaluation of executing untrusted author HTML/JavaScript inside
  authenticated LMS/CMS sessions (Moodle, WordPress, Omeka S; SCORM, H5P, eXeLearning).
  The risk is not running JavaScript but running author JavaScript in the same authenticated
  origin as the LMS; an opaque-origin + strict-sandbox + CSP + validated postMessage bridge
  preserves interactivity and SCORM tracking without trusting the content as part of the platform.
keywords:
  - LMS security
  - same-origin policy
  - iframe sandbox
  - opaque origin
  - Content Security Policy
  - SCORM
  - H5P
  - eXeLearning
  - Moodle
